{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528904","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528904"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:48:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:48:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14344"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14344"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.81,0.02,0.07,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7039"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111031"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7039"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93148"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"3716"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11061"},{"type":"tags","id":"12409"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45107"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111031"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department at 28 weeks gestation with a 12-hour history of right upper quadrant pain and nausea. She has no significant medical history and takes only prenatal vitamins. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 130/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. On abdominal examination there is some tenderness in the right upper quadrant. The uterine fundus is palpable at 27cm. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 115 g/L (110-150)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 14 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 210 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT 65 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST 55 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin 22 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe fetal CTG is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)","Ultrasound of the right upper quadrant","Computed tomography (CT) of the abdomen","24-hour urinary protein","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms suggestive of acute cholecystitis in pregnancy. The most appropriate next investigation is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound of the right upper quadrant\u003C/strong\u003E. Ultrasound is the preferred imaging modality for suspected cholecystitis in pregnancy due to its safety, availability, and ability to visualise gallstones and biliary tract dilatation without radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)\u003C/strong\u003E is a safe alternative in pregnancy and provides excellent visualisation of the biliary tree. However, it is not typically the first-line investigation due to its cost and limited availability in many emergency settings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography (CT) of the abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is generally avoided in pregnancy due to radiation exposure to the fetus. While modern CT scanners have reduced radiation doses, ultrasound or MRI are preferred when possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour urinary protein\u003C/strong\u003E test is used to diagnose pre-eclampsia, which can present with right upper quadrant pain. However, this patient\u0027s blood pressure is normal, and there are no other signs suggestive of pre-eclampsia. Moreover, the acute onset of symptoms and fever point more towards an infectious or inflammatory process like cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that carries risks of pancreatitis and perforation. It is typically reserved for therapeutic purposes rather than initial diagnosis, and would not be appropriate as the next investigation in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while this patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with cholecystitis, HELLP syndrome should also be considered in pregnant women with right upper quadrant pain. However, HELLP syndrome typically presents in the third trimester or immediately postpartum and is characterised by haemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelets. This patient\u0027s platelet count is normal, and her liver enzymes are only mildly elevated, making HELLP syndrome less likely. Nonetheless, close monitoring of her blood pressure and laboratory values is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cholecystitis can present in pregnancy, particularly in the second and third trimesters.","Ultrasound is the preferred imaging modality for suspected cholecystitis in pregnancy.","HELLP syndrome typically presents in the third trimester or immediately postpartum and is characterised by haemolysis, elevated liver enzymes, and low platelets."],"references":["Mendez-Sanchez N, Chavez-Tapia NC, Uribe M. Pregnancy and gallbladder disease: Symposium on liver \u0026 pregnancy. Annals of Hepatology. 2006;5(3):201-3. doi:10.1016/S1665-2681(19)32018-6."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93148"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14344"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93148"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-07T14:53:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-07T14:53:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7039"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111031"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7